07172nam a22013815i 9780691228327DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222000nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759492  a97806912283277 a10.1515/97806912283272doi  a(DE-B1597)576617  a(OCoLC)1312725957  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aE209 4aE209 7aHIS0360302bisacsh1 aSobel, Mechal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTeach Me Dreams :bThe Search for Self in the Revolutionary Era /cMechal Sobel. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b34 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. "Teach me Dreams": Learning to Use Dreams to Refashion the Self -- t2. Whites' Black Alien Other -- t3. Blacks' White Enemy Other -- t4. "Making Men What They Should Be" -- t5. Women Seeking What They Would Be -- tCoda "In Dreams Begins Responsibility" -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne day in 1698, Robert Pyle of Pennsylvania decided to buy a black slave. The next night he dreamed of a steep ladder to heaven that he felt he could not climb because he carried a black pot. In the dream, a man told him the ladder was the light of Jesus Christ and would bear any whose faith held strong; otherwise, the climber would fall. Pyle woke that morning positive that he should eschew slaves and slavery, having equated the pot with the slave he wished to buy. In fact, so acutely did this dream awaken him to his sins that he became a dynamic advocate of liberation. This dream literally changed his outlook and his life. Teach Me Dreams delves into the dream world of ordinary Americans and finds that as their self-perception increased, transforming them on a personal level, so did a revolutionary spirit that wrought momentous political changes. Mechal Sobel considers dreams recorded in the life narratives of 100 people, revealing the America of the Revolutionary Era to have been a truly dream-infused culture in which analysis of dreams was encouraged, and subsequent personal reevaluation was striking. Sobel uses a wealth of information--letters, diaries, and over 200 published autobiographies from a wide range of "ordinary" people; black, white, male, female. In these accounts, many previously neglected by historians, dreamers explain how their nighttime adventures opened their eyes to aspects of themselves, or unveiled new paths they should take both personally and politically. Such paths often led them to challenge those in power. Charting the widely dreamed of opposition between blacks and whites, men and women, Sobel offers astounding new insights into how early Americans understood their lives. Her analysis of the dreams and lives of ordinary Revolutionary-Era people demonstrates links between dreaming, self reevaluation, and participation in the radically changing politics of the time. This book will appeal to specialists in the fields of American and African-American history, and anyone interested in dreams and self-development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey1783-1850xHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican prose literaturey1783-1850xHistory and criticism. 0aDreamsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th centuryvSources. 0aDreamsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aEmotionsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 0aSelf-perceptionzUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 0aSocial interactionzUnited StatesxHistoryvSources. 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2